chordpro:
{title: When I Survey the Wondrous Cross}
{subtitle: Isaac Watts, 1707 — Hamburg tune by Lowell Mason (1824)}
{key: F}
{time: 4/4}
{tempo: 72}
{comment: Watts published this in 1707 as part of "Hymns and Spiritual Songs." The closing line — "my soul, my life, my all" — is perhaps the most-quoted in English hymnody.}

{start_of_verse: 1}
[F]When I sur[C]vey the [Dm]wondrous [Bb]cross
[F]On which the [C]Prince of [F]glory died
[F]My richest [C]gain I [Dm]count but [Bb]loss
[F]And pour con[C]tempt on [F]all my pride
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 2}
[F]Forbid it, [C]Lord, that [Dm]I should [Bb]boast
[F]Save in the [C]death of [F]Christ my God!
[F]All the [C]vain things [Dm]that charm me [Bb]most
[F]I sacri[C]fice them [F]to His blood
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 3}
[F]See from His [C]head, His [Dm]hands, His [Bb]feet
[F]Sorrow and [C]love flow [F]mingled down!
[F]Did e'er such [C]love and [Dm]sorrow [Bb]meet
[F]Or thorns com[C]pose so [F]rich a crown?
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: 4}
[F]Were the whole [C]realm of [Dm]nature [Bb]mine
[F]That were a [C]present [F]far too small;
[F]Love so a[C]mazing, [Dm]so di[Bb]vine
[F]Demands my [C]soul, my [F]life, my all
{end_of_verse}
